title: U.S. Olympic Training Center Velodrome Open Training Series
2016 Winter Structured Training
description: Tuesday evening structured training sessions at the Colorado Springs Olympic training Center velodrome, alternating Tuesdays in January and February. Sessions are two hours long, from 6:00 to 8:00 pm starting Tuesday January 5, 2016. These sessions are designed for experienced track riders (category 1,2,3) men and women. Unlike open track time time, structured sessions are organized to integrate everyone in race specific preparation. For example, we will organize points race training behind a motor, madison practices, team event practices (team pursuit, team sprint starts), keirin training with a motor, etc. The Tuesday night winter race series will begin after the December training events, so riders who do the structured training will be well prepared for winter track racing! These sessions are promoted by Tierra Plan Racing, and will be led by Kevin Knapp (Tierra Plan Racing) and Andy Sparks (US Track Team coach).
registration: Register onsite. No late fee for onsite registration. Riders must hold a valid USA Cycling license. Registration includes all fees including the OTC daily track usage fee.
notes: Contact Kevin Knapp with questions at knapp_kevin@hotmail.com Updates will be posted on the Tierra Plan Racing Facebook page and the Velodrome Facebook page.

description: Start and finish in Monument, Colorado at the Pikes Peak Brewery. title: 2016 UCI Mountain Bike DH World Championships
Monarch Crest Crank
description: The Monarch Crest Crank is the historic fundraiser for the Chaffee County Alliance Against Domestic Abuse (AADA) and 2016 will be the best year yet.  The Crest Crank will be the final day of Salida Bike Fest week which includes days of fun for cyclists of all abilities and their families. This is the Crest Crank’s 18th year and AADA will continue to offer mountain bikers the chance to ride the famed Monarch Crest Trail, as it has since 1998. Come join us in the fun and help raise funds to support the important work of AADA. This year the Monarch Crest Trail ride will be on Sunday, September 18, 2016!
course:
Known as one of the Top Ten Mountain Bike Rides in America, the Monarch Crest Trail is definitely one of the best rides you will ever do.  The ride starts on top of Monarch Pass at a lofty 11,312 feet and quickly climbs to the Continental Divide.  The singletrack follows the Divide for 10 miles above treeline through rock gardens and fields of wildflowers, climbs steep hills and drops back into thick pine forests. It’s pure singletrack and so fun.  On clear days, you can see all the way from Pikes Peak to the San Juan Mountains – the entire width of the Colorado Rockies.

After riding the Monarch Crest Trail, you have a choice of either riding down the challenging Silver Creek singletrack or choosing an easier route down the smooth dirt road of Marshall Pass.

Silver Creek is a fantastic, fun and rough skinny trail with some rocky challenges.  Marshall Pass is non-technical, an old Otto Mears railroad route that lets a mountain biker look up and enjoy the amazing Colorado Rocky Mountain scenery all around.
registration:
Entry remains $75, plus pledges, for the Monarch Crest Trail ride.  On top of this bargain price, we highly encourage you to raise at least the same amount in personal pledges and sponsorships, and great prizes for riders raising pledges above certain levels. We also have a sweet Silent Auction after the ride at the Riverside Park.

Your entry fee for the adult rides includes the ride, guide, shuttle and of course, our legendary party in Riverside Park after the ride. The top fundraiser bringing in more than $500 of pledges wins a stylish new cruiser bike.

We are anticipating close to 100 riders this year, and as we continue our collaboration with Salida Bike Fest, we are expecting a few hundred attendees at the super fun after-party at Riverside Park. The after-party will feature live music from local bands, libations, food, fun and funky bike art by local artists, and a competitive silent auction.
notes:
You must have your mountain bike ready to load on the shuttle on arrival – no last minute repairs or bike checks.

On Sept 18th, be at  Salida Bike Company (148 North F Street) at  7:45am – 8:00am if you have already registered, earlier if not. Shuttles leave at 8:30am sharp from  Salida Bike Company.

We will load our bikes into the shuttle buses and drive to the summit of Monarch Pass for an early start.  Here we will start the faster riders and guides first and the slower riders second.

Faster riders can complete the ride in 3-4 hours.  Slower riders will need 5 hours.  The ride will officially end at the Shirley Site trailhead where shuttle buses will drive us back to Historic Downtown Salida for a great party in Riverside Park.

(Riders may choose to continue past Shirley Site and ride back to Salida, but this is where the Monarch Crest Crank officially ends, so you are on your own and not covered by event insurance past this point.  The ride from Shirley Site to Salida is an additional 13 miles.)
directions: On Sept 18th, be at  Salida Bike Company (148 North F Street) at  7:45am – 8:00am if you have already registered, earlier if not. Shuttles leave at 8:30am sharp from  Salida Bike Company.

Butter's Private Parts Cyclocross (at Robson's Ranch)
description: Every year the challenge for ‘cross devotees heading to Nationals is staying wound up and motivated for three race-free weekends. Well get up off your knees and stop praying because butter has got your back. Butter presents Private Parts ‘cross, two weekends of grass roots training races to keep your afterburners hot coming up to the biggest, fastest and hardest race of the season. We're keeping it simple. Three categories; A,B,C. Sign up,  self-select, throw down. The course at Butter Ranch has velcro grass, hills, ass-kickin' straights and batshit crazy handling sections. if it rains or snows it will only get better.
course: A twisty, tight, fun, and rolling pocket sized course in beautiful Longmont, Colorado.  This is the essence of US Cyclocross:  getting together with your buddies and rolling around in the yard. The course at Butter Ranch has velcro grass, hills, ass-kickin' straights and batshit crazy handling sections. If it rains or snows it will only get better.
registration: Registration is at http://www.wearebutter.com/private-parts-cx/.   WE REALLY, REALLY would like you to pre register.  There are 40 spots per category per day, and that's it.  If you turn up on event day and your category is full, we are going to turn you away or make you go in a different category
notes: This is a non-competitive event designed to keep skills and fitness sharp at the end of December, getting ready for Nationals, and tearing up Robson's yard.  You decide which group you want to ride in, because we don't really care.  Register, roll around and stay fit.  If you want to know who you beat, get a pencil and write down the names of the people behind you.
directions: Google this address: 6152 Hygiene Rd, Longmont, CO, 80503
